The following boxplots indicate the distribution of the records for thr FG values at different times and for different treatments. For instance, as a quick summary, for early stages of FG values there is a larger quantity of records for treatment. The lowest median lies for treatment 3 and the largest whiskers for treatment 1 and 3. Both treatment 2 and 3 include outliers. For FG values for month 3 all box heights appear very equal between treatments being treatment 2 the one with the lowest median and treatment 1 the one with the longest whiskers. Box heights differ for FG values for month 6 being treatment 3 the one with the highest box height and 2 the lowest. Treatment 1 and 2 both appear to have outliers and treatment 0 appears to have the highest mean above all treatments. Finally, for FG values for month 12 the highest median belongs to treatment 0 but the outliers lie in treatmetn 1 and 2. The highest variability for values ofr FGm12 lie for treatment 3. For the second batch of boxplots, it can be seen how the PG values decrease as month 12 approaches for all values, being Treatment 2 the one with the highest decrease between month 0 and 12. ##Modeling FGm12

First a model with all the variables and without smoothing is fitted.

Looking at the summary, it can be seen that the only significant variable is FGm0. All the other variables, SysPres, DiaPres,weight, and height are not significant. Next the same model but with all the variables smoothed is fitted:

mod1s <- gam(FGm12~s(SysPres)+s(DiaPres)+s(weight)+s(height)+s(FGm0)+Treatment, data = hirs)
